{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3acaa00d-0ec9-455d-bf45-cb9476166b8a","content":"Both of those properties are **Xamarin.Forms APIs** and the tutorial you found is likely outdated. Here's the situation for .NET MAUI on .NET 10:\n\n### `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"`\n**Not needed.** In .NET MAUI, pages respect the safe area **by default** — content is automatically inset from the notch, Dynamic Island, and home indicator. There's no need to opt in.\n\n### `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` on a Grid\n**Not a real MAUI property.** This doesn't exist on layout views in .NET MAUI. If you try to use it, you'll get a XAML compilation error.\n\n### What to do instead\n\nTo extend a background image **into** the safe area (behind the notch), use negative margins or an `AbsoluteLayout` that fills the full page, then keep your interactive content inside the default safe padding:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui\"\n             xmlns:x=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml\">\n    <Grid>\n        <!-- Background image fills entire screen including unsafe areas -->\n        <Image Source=\"background.png\"\n               Aspect=\"AspectFill\"\n               Margin=\"-50\" />\n\n        <!-- Content stays within safe area via default page padding -->\n        <VerticalStackLayout Padding=\"20\">\n            <Label Text=\"Hello, iPhone!\" />\n        </VerticalStackLayout>\n    </Grid>\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\nIf you need **programmatic control** over safe area insets, use `On<iOS>().SetUseSafeArea(bool)` in code-behind — but this is rarely needed since the default behavior is already correct.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"076ae5a4-a6c7-405b-8a72-8a9847a578fe","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI safe area handling on iOS, specifically about two properties:\n\n1. `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` - a platform-specific property for ContentPage\n2. `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` - a property on Grid for background images\n\nLet me search for information about these APIs in the current repository context, and also think about what I know about .NET MAUI.\n\nIn .NET MAUI (and Xamarin.Forms before it), safe area handling on iOS has evolved:\n\n1. `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` - This was a Xamarin.Forms iOS platform-specific. In .NET MAUI, the approach changed. In .NET MAUI, safe area is handled differently - there's padding-based approaches or the `Page.IgnoreSafeArea` property.\n\n\n2. `IgnoreSafeArea` - In Xamarin.Forms, there was no such property directly on layouts. In .NET MAUI, there have been changes. Pages respect the safe area by default in .NET MAUI, with content inset from the notch or home indicator, but if you want a view like a background image to extend into the safe area, you'd need a different approach than what these properties provide. In .NET MAUI, safe areas are handled automatically by default on iOS, so there's no need to explicitly enable `UseSafeArea` like in Xamarin.Forms. If you need content to extend into unsafe areas like behind a notch, you'd adjust padding or use layout techniques rather than ignoring the safe area entirely. I'm not entirely certain about all the specifics in .NET 10 specifically, but the `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` platform-specific should still be available if needed. The `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` property is valid in MAUI and explicitly tells pages to respect safe area insets, though this is the default behavior anyway. For `IgnoreSafeArea` on Grid, I'm not certain this exists as a direct property in MAUI—to extend a background image behind the safe area, you'd likely need a different approach, possibly working at the page level rather than on individual layout controls. I need to clarify what's actually available in .NET MAUI rather than guessing. There's no `IgnoreSafeArea` property on views or layouts—that might be from a third-party library or a misunderstanding. The real approach is that pages automatically respect safe areas by default, and if you want a background to extend into unsafe areas, you'd need to use negative margins or position the image outside the padded region.","outputTokens":1963,"requestId":"B7D2:19EA9:19C7C2:219980:69FFDB42"},"id":"4646d1a9-9b36-4a4c-8a15-563189f0de10","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:12:11.233Z","parentId":"e94d9eff-648b-4d87-99c9-069a803390af"}
